</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="74.[700,1229,193,627]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
ETYMOLOGY: The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[1148,1229,545,568]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebenus">
<emphasis box="[1148,1229,545,568]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">ebenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(of ebony, black) is a Latin adjectival. I refer to the integumentary color of these beetles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
